{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/quora-question-pairs-detecting-text-similarity-using-siamese-networks-a370f039731b", "time": 1683012571.1352131, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/quora-question-pairs-detecting-text-similarity-using-siamese-networks-a370f039731b/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Quora Question Pairs: Detecting Text Similarity using Siamese networks. | by Aadit Kapoor | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Quora Question Pairs: Detecting Text Similarity using Siamese networks.", "description": "Ever wondered how to calculate text similarity using Deep Learning? We aim to develop a model to detect text similarity between texts. We will be using the Quora Question Pairs Dataset. Like any\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/c/quora-question-pairs/data", "anchor_text": "Quora Question Pairs Dataset.", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/", "anchor_text": "https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 9}], "all_paragraphs": ["Ever wondered how to calculate text similarity using Deep Learning? We aim to develop a model to detect text similarity between texts. We will be using the Quora Question Pairs Dataset.", "Let us first start by exploring the dataset. Our dataset consists of:", "Like any Machine Learning project, we will start by preprocessing the data. Let us first load the data and combined the question1 and question2 to form the vocabulary.", "We will also clean the text a bit.", "Every feed-forward neural network that takes words from a vocabulary as input and embeds them as vectors into a lower dimensional space, which it then fine-tunes through back-propagation, necessarily yields word embeddings as the weights of the first layer, which is usually referred to as Embedding Layer (Ruder, 2016)", "Word embedding learns the syntactical and semantic aspects of the text (Almeida et al, 2019). As our problem is related to the semantic meaning of the text, we will use a word embedding as our first layer in our Siamese Network.", "For this, we will use the popular GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) embedding model. We will obtain the pre-trained model (https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/) and load it as our first layer as the embedding layer.", "Due to the nearst neighbours approach (or cosine similarity) of Glove, it is able to capture the semantic similary the word. In our model, we will use an embedding matrix developed using Glove weights and take word vectors for each of our sentence.", "First we build a Tokenizer out of all our vocabulary.", "Now assuming, we have downloaded the Glove pre-trained vectors from here, we initialize our embedding layer with the embedding matrix.", "Now we have created our embedding matrix, we will nor start building our model.", "We use an LSTM layer to encode our 100 dim word embedding. Then we calculate the Manhattan Distance (Also called L1 Distance), followed by a sigmoid activation to squash our output between 0 and 1.(1 refers to maximum similarity and 0 refers to minimum similarity). We use the MSE as our loss function and an Adam optimizer.", "We split our train.csv to train, test, and validation set to test out our model.", "To train our model, we simply call the fit function followed by the inputs.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fa370f039731b&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fquora-question-pairs-detecting-text-similarity-using-siamese-networks-a370f039731b&source=post_page---two_column